 "span": {"begin": 490, "end": 494}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9671119451522827, "span": {"begin": 559, "end": 563}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:653108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917426705360413, "span": {"begin": 641, "end": 644}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9745423197746277, "span": {"begin": 654, "end": 658}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4288"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Ki67", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9623648524284363, "span": {"begin": 678, "end": 682}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rats", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9198399186134338, "span": {"begin": 750, "end": 754}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010634"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phenobarbital", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9943168759346008, "span": {"begin": 795, "end": 808}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4616"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Gadd45b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9912428855895996, "span": {"begin": 865, "end": 872}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10912"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Gadd45g", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.996032178401947, "span": {"begin": 902, "end": 909}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010634"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phenobarbital", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980114698410034, "span": {"begin": 1051, "end": 1064}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9819552302360535, "span": {"begin": 1136, "end": 1139}}], "text": "Strong support for this linkage comes from in vivo and in vitro studies with model CAR activators, and via the absence of the same effects including specific gene expression changes and cell proliferation changes (by BrdU, PCNA or Ki67 labeling index) in CAR knockout mice lacking the CAR receptor. In a study with 850 ppm dietary phenobarbital in C3H wild-type and CAR knockout mice, increases in Cyp2b10 and Gadd45b gene expression were associated with increases in cell proliferation by Ki67 labeling index after 3 days or 7 days of treatment in wild-type mice; the increases in gene expression were abolished or substantially reduced in CAR knockout mice, and no effects on Ki67 labeling index were observed (Peffer et al., 2007). In Fischer 344 rats, Ozawa (Ozawa et al., 2011) showed that phenobarbital at 500 ppm in the diet produced a sustained increase in Gadd45b expression and a decrease in Gadd45g expression; these directions of change have been previously associated with enhanced cell proliferation. Also, doses of 500 &ndash; 1000 ppm phenobarbital have previously been shown to produce a cell proliferation response in rat liver (Deguchi et al., 2009; Kolaja et al., 1996a).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:49:03 +0000 2026"}